Page 8: TCP Reliability & Introduction to UDP
TCP Connection & Delivery:
Two computers will first establish the connection method before transferring the data.
Three-Way Handshake Diagram:
Sender sends SYN to Receiver.
Receiver sends SYN/ACK back to Sender.
Sender sends ACK.
Once this is done, the data will then be delivered.
TCP guarantees the delivery of the data.
If anything goes wrong with any data packet, TCP will resend them without any problem.
UDP (User Datagram Protocol)
UDP is also used for sending and receiving data.
It is a connection-less oriented protocol.
It does not establish a session and does not guarantee that data has been delivered.
The sender sends data and does not really care if the data is received at the other end.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Page 9: UDP Characteristics & Use Cases
UDP Workflow:
It does not use SYN/ACK before or during sending.
It does not care if the receiver is getting the data or not.
UDP is known as the "fire & forget protocol" because it sends data and doesn't care what happens to it.
No data guarantee transmission can be held by UDP.
"UDP is faster than TCP".
Characteristics of UDP:
Connection-less.
No guarantee of delivery.
Faster.
No ordering.
Used In:
Video streaming.
Online games.
Voice calls (e.g., Zoom, WhatsApp)